# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: larry-page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port of New York Authority began acquiring the land on the building's site in 1930, against the protests of local residents.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] It was completed in 1932 and served as an inland terminal for the Hudson River piers and as a warehousing and industrial facility.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Occupancy fell to 50 percent in the 1970s due to the decline of industrial activity in Manhattan, and the Port Authority itself moved to the World Trade Center in 1973.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In the 1990s the building began to attract tenants in the technology and telecommunications sectors.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In 2010, the building was purchased for $1.8 billion by Google, who became its largest tenant; Google's presence helped attract other technology companies to Chelsea and contributed to the neighborhood's ongoing gentrification.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Aside from Google, the building is also home to a cancer treatment center and a black box theater.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] 111 Eighth Avenue occupies the full city block between Eighth and Ninth Avenues and 15th and 16th Streets in the Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building, completed in 1932, was designed by Lusby Simpson of Abbott, Merkt & Co.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building is 15 stories tall and has 2.9 million square feet (270,000 m2) of floor space, more than the Empire State Building; the individual floors are nearly 4 acres (1.6 ha) in area and have 14.5-foot (4.4 m) ceilings.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] It has a rooftop helipad and penthouse floors on either end of the building.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Its exterior is in the Art Deco style and features recurring seagull motifs.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The walls are largely made of brick, with granite bases; the first two stories are limestone, and copings and finials are of terracotta.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Because of the warehouse mission of the building, it was able to avoid some of the setback rules that greatly reduced the buildable space available for the skyscrapers that mark the Manhattan skyline.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building had a multipurpose design when it opened in 1932, with the first floor and basement designated as "Union Inland Terminal #1", which was to be used to transport goods by truck to and from railroad lines and shipping piers on the Hudson River.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Cargo was dropped off along 15th Street, sorted inside the building, and picked up from the 16th Street side.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building included four truck elevators, each of which had a 40,000-pound (18,000 kg; 20-short-ton) capacity and could travel at up to 200 ft/min (61 m/min).
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] These elevators measured 17 by 34 feet (5.2 by 10.4 m) across, and they lifted trucks into pits measuring 3.5 feet (1.1 m) deep and 38 by 90 feet (12 by 27 m) across.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] There were also 12 package elevators and 18 passenger elevators.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Freight companies used the elevators to deliver cargo directly to tenants, in contrast to other industrial buildings in New York City, where cargo was dropped off at ground level.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The second floor contained Commerce Hall, designed for exhibitions.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The upper floors were intended for manufacturing.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] There were 16 loading docks on each floor.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] On the 15th floor, which contained the Port Authority's offices, engineer Aymar Embury II designed a 325-seat auditorium decorated in green and blue.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The *New York Herald Tribune* said was the "first auditorium designed for commercial purposes in a strictly commercial structure".
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building's design retains vestiges of its original industrial purpose, including truck-sized freight elevators and floors built to support heavy loads.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] As of 2008, two of its original truck elevators were still in use, in addition to nine other large freight elevators and fourteen passenger elevators.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The floors of the two lobbies originally each had a large bronze seal of the Port Authority embedded in them; one of these was removed and converted into a coffee table as a retirement gift for Port Authority director Austin J.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] It is also noted for its unobstructed views of the Manhattan skyline.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building has direct access to the 14th Street/Eighth Avenue station of the New York City Subway; when the building opened, a staircase at 15th Street and Eighth Avenue led directly to the subway station in the basement.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] By the early twentieth century, the West Side of Manhattan was plagued with heavy traffic because of the tangle of street-level passenger and freight trains on the West Side Line, cargo unloading from the busy Hudson River piers, and the lack of suitable warehouse facilities.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The situation led the Port of New York Authority to commission the construction of a large inland terminal at 111 Eighth Avenue.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] It was designed to alleviate the traffic problem by streamlining the distribution of goods within a single location.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Instead of cargo being picked up directly at the piers, it would be brought to the building to be consolidated, where trucks could pick up all their cargo in a single stop.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] A concurrent project, the West Side Improvement Project, replaced the West Side Line with the original High Line elevated railway, which ran a few blocks away from 111 Eighth Avenue; it began full operation in 1934.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In May 1930, the Port Authority and all of the railroads in the Port of New York agreed to build a "union inland freight terminal" between Eighth Avenue, 15th Street, Ninth Avenue, and 16th Street.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal was planned to cost $15 million and would include office space, as well as large driveways and about 7 acres (28,000 m2; 300,000 ft2) for sorting freight.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The structure was to be known as Inland Terminal No.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] 1 because the Port Authority hoped that similar freight terminals would be constructed across the city.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] At the time of the announcement, the Port Authority already owned half of the block, which it had acquired for $1.5 million.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Most of the block had been occupied by houses, except for a factory in the middle of the block on 15th Street.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The New York City Board of Estimate approved the proposed terminal's site in June 1930.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority acquired additional land on the building's site throughout the rest of the year, despite the protests of local residents.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] By October 1930, the Port Authority had bought 85 percent of the site and was preparing to acquire the remaining buildings through condemnation.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] A contract for the demolition of existing structures was awarded in December 1930.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Twelve railroads signed an agreement with the Port Authority to use the new terminal at the beginning of January 1931, and contractors immediately began razing the site.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Godwin Construction Company was contracted in April 1931 to excavate the site and construct the building's foundations.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] A groundbreaking ceremony for the freight terminal, attended by New York State governor Franklin D.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Roosevelt, took place on April 30, 1931.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] That September, the Port Authority received bids for the construction of the building's superstructure; the Turner Construction Company submitted a low bid of $7.591 million.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Construction required 120,000 cubic yards of concrete, 65 miles of piping, and 12 million bricks, as well as 160,000 barrels of cement.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority also paid to widen the streets on all four sides.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Four hundred railroad managers were invited to inspect the new terminal on September 9, 1932.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] 1 was formally dedicated the next week, September 16, though the building was not at that time fully completed.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] At the time it was the largest building in New York City.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building ultimately cost $16 million; the superstructure alone cost $8 million to $9 million.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Shippers and consignees began using a 265,000-square-foot (24,600 m2) freight terminal on the basement and first floor on October 3, 1932.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Only the basement and ground story were open at the time; the upper stories, intended for light manufacturing, were not expected to be completed until the end of the year.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Real-estate experts cited Inland Terminal No.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] 1 as one of several developments that were contributing to the growth of businesses in Chelsea.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The final dedication of the building occurred on February 25, 1933, with a ceremony attended by Port Authority, New York City, and New York state officials.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] A banquet was held in one of the building's truck elevators to mark its dedication.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Tenants had begun moving into the upper stories even before the building's dedication.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] By the beginning of 1933, eight hundred shipping firms were using the terminal to ship outbound freight, while fifty shippers received inbound freight there.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Each railroad paid the Port Authority ten cents for every 1 short ton (0.89 long tons; 0.91 t) of freight handled at the terminal.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal was to be used by all shippers in Manhattan between Houston Street to the south and 23rd Street to the north.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] At the time of construction it was estimated to be capable of handling one-third of the 680,000 annual tons of less-than-carload freight at the port.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Among the terminal's tenants during the 1930s were the Woolworth Company, Rand McNally, the New York Trust Company, and offices of the Works Progress Administration.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority hired Caldwell, Garvan & Bettini in October 1933 to construct a lobby, stair, and foyer for Commerce Hall on the building's second floor.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Commerce Hall opened on December 8, 1933, with an exhibit of Ford Motor Company vehicles.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal saw early success in reducing truck traffic to and from the railheads.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] For instance, on May 25, 1936, 250 trucks brought cargo to the building that was consolidated into only 37 trucks to take to the ferry terminals.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Commerce Hall hosted the National Business Show for several years in the 1930s.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] By February 1938, all of the building's space had been rented, despite the ongoing Great Depression.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] After Commerce Hall was closed in 1938, the floor was converted to regular commercial use.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Board of Estimate approved an agreement in 1940, in which the Port Authority would make annual $60,000 payments in lieu of taxes on the building.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building remained 95 percent occupied at the time.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Its tenants during the early 1940s included Sears, Roebuck and Company, as well as a regional office for the Second Corps Area.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In spite of a decline in freight traffic during World War II, the Port Authority retained a good credit rating and, by 1945, had drawn up plans for two new freight terminals in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority's 1949 report noted a significant decrease in freight handling at the building due to an overall shift in Manhattan from rail to trucks for transporting goods.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Around this time, the Port Authority constructed additional inland terminals intended for truck traffic: the New York Union Motor Truck Terminal in 1949 and the Newark Union Motor Truck Terminal in 1950.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority began erecting a helipad on the building's roof in November 1950, and the helipad opened on May 31, 1951.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] It was the site of an accident on July 13, 1955, when a Bell 47 helicopter operated by the Port Authority crashed shortly after take-off and fell, in flames, onto the fifteenth floor, where it became stuck.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The pilot and his only passenger survived with injuries.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The last of the railroad companies left the building in 1963.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The shipping and manufacturing industries in Chelsea declined significantly during the 1960s, as firms moved from the neighborhood to elsewhere in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building remained the Port Authority's headquarters until the agency moved to the new World Trade Center in 1973.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority sold 111 Eighth Avenue to Realopco Inc. – a company operated by brothers Sylvan Lawrence and Seymour Cohn, who also led the Sylvan Lawrence Company – for $24 million in July 1973.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The owners added a CCTV system, replaced existing manually operated elevators with 12 automatic elevators, and refurbished the lobby, and they received a $25 million mortgage from Chase Manhattan Bank.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building had a 40 percent vacancy rate in 1975, a figure that increased the next year to 50 percent.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] This was attributed to the decline of manufacturing in New York City and the ongoing national recession; in addition, several tenants had vacated large blocks of space, including Interstate Stores and Atlantic Department Stores.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Mayor Abraham Beame proposed that the vacant space be leased to garment manufacturers, but many garment firms were loath to relocate.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] After the Sorg Printing Company leased some of the vacant space, the occupancy rate increased to 75 percent by January 1977.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Occupancy had rebounded to 90 percent by 1979.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Following Lawrence's death in 1981, Seymour Cohn and Lawrence's widow Alice each acquired a 50 percent stake in 111 Eighth Avenue.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Cohn and Alice Lawrence were unable to agree on what to do with 111 Eighth Avenue and three other buildings, leading to a protracted legal struggle.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] During the 1980s and 1990s, the building attracted a number of a tenants in the computer industry, who were drawn by the large floor space.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In addition, numerous companies had moved their back office operations to 111 Eighth Avenue by the early 1980s.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building was 80 percent occupied in 1992, with space renting at $8 to $18 per square foot ($86 to $194/m2).
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] By the late 1990s, the building was 87 percent occupied, and Sylvan Lawrence had leased out 200,000 square feet (19,000 m2) during the preceding year.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building's largest tenants at the time included Citibank, the New York State Insurance Fund, and Prudential Securities.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The massive building served as a dwindling warehouse and back-office outpost through the end of the 1990s.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Cohn and Alice Lawrence agreed to sell off 111 Eighth Avenue and Lawrence's other three buildings in 1997.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Blackacre Capital Group and Taconic Investment Partners agreed to acquire the four buildings in November 1997 for $387 million; the sale was finalized in January 1998.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic marketed 111 Eighth Avenue as a carrier hotel for the new booming internet business, as the building had high ceilings, large floor plates, multiple fiber-optic connections, and five times the electrical capacity that typical tenants required.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] This was coupled with the fashionable rise of the Chelsea neighborhood that surrounded it.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic began a $50 million renovation, replacing the building's wiring.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] One-third of the space was leased to telecommunications companies and another one-third to advertising agencies and internet companies.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The new occupants could afford higher rents than the old industrial tenants.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Although Taconic tried to screen potential telecommunications tenants by establishing strict net-worth requirements, so many companies expressed interest in the building that Taconic had stopped accepting new telecommunications tenants by late 1999.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Average rents had more than doubled during the preceding two years, from $18 to $46 per square foot ($190 to $500/m2).
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] A 70,000-square-foot (6,500 m2) cancer treatment center, designed by Gwathmey Siegel & Associates Architects and operated by St.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Vincent's Hospital, opened in the building the same year.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Eighth and Ninth Avenue lobbies were renovated in 2000 and 2004, respectively.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] During the Northeast blackout of 2003, the building was able to keep power on, thanks to an underground fuel tank and 37 generators.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In 2006, the Atlantic Theater Company opened a 99-seat black box theater in the building, and Lifetime Entertainment Services became its first cable television tenant.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Google opened its largest engineering office outside of California in the building in 2006, leasing 300,000 square feet (28,000 m2) across three floors.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Google workspace was noted for its campus-like and playful atmosphere, with perks including free food and a game room; *The New York Times* described it as "a vision of a workplace utopia as conceived by rich, young, single engineers in Silicon Valley, transplanted to Manhattan".
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In 2010, Google contracted to purchase the entire building from Taconic, in a deal reported to be worth around $1.8 billion, the biggest purchase of a U.S. office building of the year.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The deal was credited with helping revive the New York City commercial real estate market, which had slumped during the Great Recession.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] After the purchase, Google was the largest tenant, with 500,000 square feet (46,000 m2) of the building.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic continued to manage the building under contract from Google.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Since its acquisition, the building has become popularly known as the "Google Building", and it is regarded as the company's East Coast headquarters.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] 111 Eighth Avenue is adjacent to trunk fiber optic lines stretching from Hudson Street and continuing up Ninth Avenue.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] That line at the time was owned by Lexent Metro Connect.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] There was speculation at the time of the acquisition that Google would use its strategic location to launch a Google Fiber operation in New York City.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Google Fiber plan never came to pass, and Google has denied it has any plans to bring it to New York City anytime in the near future, although in 2013 it did begin offering free Wi-Fi to its Chelsea neighbors.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The Lexent dark fiber line has been acquired by Lightower Fiber Networks.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] The building's meet-me room in its carrier hotel was one of the main network interconnections in the city as of 2006.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] In 2013 the first class of the newly created Cornell NYC Tech school began classes in the building, in space donated by Google.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Classes continued in the building until the school moved to its new location on Roosevelt Island in 2017.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Despite the massive size of the acquisition, Google has still found itself having to rent space elsewhere because it has been unable to break the leases with some of its tenants, including Nike, Deutsch Inc., and Bank of New York.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] After years of renting additional space across the street in the Chelsea Market, Google purchased that building in 2018.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] Google's expansion in Chelsea helped attract other technology companies to the area and contributed to gentrification.
[src:larry-page/111-eighth-avenue] *The New York Times* described Google as drawing "relatively few complaints" in the neighborhood, and New York City Council speaker Corey Johnson called the company "a good neighbor", although some residents blamed it for changing the neighborhood's character and driving out smaller businesses.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The **1993 Maize & Blue solar car** was built by the University of Michigan Solar Car Team during the period from 1990 to 1993.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The car won a national championship in Sunrayce 93, the predecessor race to the North American Solar Challenge.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] It then went on to finish 11th in the 1993 World Solar Challenge.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue is now part of the permanent display at the Museum of Science and Industry in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The car had an evolutionary design descended from the General Motors Sunraycer and the University of Michigan's first generation car, Sunrunner.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The car is considered an early example of and demonstration platform for energy efficient automobile design.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The University of Michigan Solar Car Team was founded in 1989 and has been in continuous existence since.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The team, composed of University graduate and undergraduate students as well as faculty advisers has competed in many major races including the World Solar Challenge and the North American Solar Challenge.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The team that raced in 1993 was the second generation "Maize & Blue" team (team tradition dictates that each team names their car and that team is known by the name of their car).
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The Maize & Blue team was formally established in October 1990 and completed in December 1993.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Over a unique three-year period for the team, they designed the car, built a prototype chassis, tested the prototype, built the race vehicle and then tested that vehicle in preparation for the two races.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The team was founded by a few individuals and grew to its peak of several hundred students from all academic disciplines.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] During design and construction, the team was at its largest in numbers.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] During testing and the actual races, the team shrunk to a core group dubbed the "race crew" composed of approximately 30 students and advisers.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Over the course of the project the team included at least 260 student members (see list of known team members below).
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Note that not all team members participated for the duration of the project (more than 3 years) or contributed the same amount of time and effort.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] One team member of note is Larry Page, seen at the top left of the photo at right, co-founder of Google, who participated in the early phase of the project but did not play a significant role in the final phases.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] In total approximately 70,000 hours of student labor were invested in the project.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue combined technology typically used in the aerospace, bicycle, alternative energy and automotive industries.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Unlike typical race cars, Maize & Blue was designed with severe energy constraints imposed by the race regulations.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] These rules limited the energy to only that collected from solar radiation and as a result optimizing the design to account for aerodynamic drag, vehicle weight, rolling resistance and electrical efficiency were paramount.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Conventional thinking had to be challenged, for example, rather than a conventional automobile seat which would weigh tens of pounds, Maize & Blue employed a nylon mesh seat combined with a five-point harness that weighed less than 3 pounds.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] One of the cutting edge, at the time, processes that the team employed in designing Maize & Blue was computer aided design.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] CAD was used to design almost all of the car using Dassault Systèmes' CATIA and then modeling the physical characteristics using SDRC I-DEAS and other programs most running on some IBM RS/6000 Unix workstations donated by team sponsor IBM.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] At the time, CATIA was being used to design the Boeing 777, the first commercial airplane fully designed using CAD.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Initially several hand built foam quarter scale models were constructed and tested in the University of Michigan's subsonic low turbulence 5' x 7' wind tunnel.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] This testing was instrumental in determining the ultimate vehicle configuration.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Once finalized, the body of the car was NC milled in quarter scale from the CATIA model and verified in wind tunnel testing.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] On May 8, 1993, Maize & Blue was tested in a full scale wind tunnel at Lockheed's facility in Atlanta, GA.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Obtaining cash and in-kind donations was critical to the completion of Maize & Blue.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Early on in the project, the team created a dedicated group focused on raising funds.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Team sponsors ranged from the University of Michigan itself to corporate sponsors and university alumni.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] In total, there were hundreds of sponsors who contributed to the project.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Corporate sponsors included Ford Motor Company, IBM, Northwest Airlines, General Motors, 3M, Magnetek, TRW, Monroe, BASF, Dana Holding Corporation and many others.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Among the individual alumni sponsors, University of Michigan alumni Charles Hutchins stood out as a major contributor.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Component, system and vehicle testing was a continual process throughout the project and began very early on in early 1991.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] An initial vehicle design for Maize & Blue had a three-wheel configuration with one wheel in front which afforded significantly improved aerodynamics but introduced handling concerns.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] In 1991, the team built a "test buck" which was used to evaluate the handling characteristics of the tricycle configuration.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] As a result of these tests, the design was abandoned in favor of a more conventional, and more stable, four-wheel configuration.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] In early 1992, the team constructed a prototype chassis based on the final vehicle design for Maize & Blue.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] This prototype chassis was tested in excess of 1,000 miles on closed courses, primarily the Michigan International Speedway in Brooklyn, Michigan.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] A final round of vehicle testing was conducted in San Angelo, Texas, at the Goodyear Proving Grounds and on nearby roads.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Also, the team completed three days of testing on the actual race route the week prior to the start of the race (primarily to get a feel for the actual route and traffic patterns).
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] There were three qualifiers for Sunrayce 93; the first two several months prior to the race start and the third "last chance" qualifier held in the weeks before the actual race start.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The qualifiers were used to determine that the vehicles met all of the race regulations and also to determine the starting positions.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue completed the qualifier held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway and qualified to start in the 10th position.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The race was held over seven days from June 20–26, 1993.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The race began at the recently opened Ballpark in Arlington (now known as Ameriquest Field) in Arlington, Texas and finished at the Minnesota Zoo in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] By the end of the first race day, Maize & Blue had moved from 10th into 1st place, just a few minutes ahead of the second place car from Cal Poly Pomona.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Pre-race favorite Cal State LA suffered debilitating electrical failures on day 1 putting them out of contention for the remainder of the race.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Over the next three days, the team jockeyed for position at one point falling behind first place by as much as 20 minutes, primarily due to two penalties levied by race officials for violation of traffic rules.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] On day 5 of the race, the weather forecast called for rain and overcast conditions for most of the day.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue was the only car to finish that leg of the race under its own power (the Iowa State University car finished ahead of Michigan, but incurred a 10-hour penalty for replacing their battery pack at the start of the day).
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] On day 5, the Michigan team accumulated a 90-minute lead over the next fastest car.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Days 6 and 7 were uneventful with Maize & Blue maintaining its lead and finishing in first place overall followed by Cal Poly Pomona in second and Cal State LA in third.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue finished with an average speed of 27.29 mph over the 1100-mile course edging out the second place car by 90 minutes.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] The victory gave Michigan its second consecutive national championship in solar car racing.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Martin Green at the University of New South Wales.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Unfortunately, as a result of an assembly flaw during the encapsulation process the new cells were unable to produce peak power output resulting in *lower* total array power.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] There were other minor changes to the vehicle designed to reduce weight or aerodynamic drag (the most notable with the removal of all decals except those required by race officials).
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue finished in 11th place in the 1993 World Solar Challenge.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Honda won the 1993 World Solar Challenge followed by the team from Biel University.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Maize & Blue finished the race ahead of the 1990 University of Michigan Sunrunner's record of 5 days, but that was not enough for a top finish.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] After the two races, the team set about finding a permanent home for its car, Maize & Blue.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] At the conclusion of a several month long process, the car was donated and accepted into the permanent display at the Museum of Science and Industry in Chicago, where it now resides as part of its Transportation Gallery exhibit.
[src:larry-page/1993-maize-blue-university-of-michigan-solar-car] Beginning in early 1994, the Maize & Blue team began the transfer and hand over to the third-generation team and thus concluded the project.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The **2011 Slovenian YouTube incident** was the publication of three clips of the recordings of closed sessions of the Government of Slovenia on the video-sharing website YouTube on 3 December 2011.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The clips were published under the title *Stari obrazi* (*Old Faces*) by someone who signed himself as *stariobrazi* (*oldfaces*).
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The publication happened during the term of the Prime Minister Borut Pahor, just before the early 2011 Slovenian parliamentary election on 4 December.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The first of the clips published was dated to 31 January 2008, when Janez Janša was the Prime Minister.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The second and the third clip was dated to 23 April 2009, respectively 23 April and 30 April 2009, when Borut Pahor was the Prime Minister.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The original recordings were produced in audio and video.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were stored on DVDs and locked in a safe available only to authorised personnel.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were also available at home to three people via the Spectiva remote viewing software, but due to their low quality, the probability of Spectiva being the source of the leaked data has been estimated as low, and it was not used during the term of Pahor's government.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Spectiva could be misused until July 2009.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] It seems most probable that the recordings originated from the recording room or were transferred with additional equipment from the press room of the government; till 2009, sessions were broadcast live there so that extracts of resolutions could be made by the authorised personnel.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Marjan Miklavčič, an expert in intelligence services and a lecturer at the University of Maribor, compared the publication to WikiLeaks.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] He particularly stressed that it was not known which data had been stolen and whether they could be used for extortion.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Iztok Prezelj, who lectures on intelligence at the University of Ljubljana, stated that the publication showed a parallel state to exist in Slovenia.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Miklavčič confirmed that all the data publicly available indicate the thesis about a parallel state to be correct.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The ministers of Janša's government, Andrej Vizjak and Mojca Kucler Dolinar, were discussing the wages of judges.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 9 December, it was reported that the Slovenian Police had started investigation about the clips.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 14 December, the Government spokesperson Darijan Košir explained that in 2006, government areas were renovated.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] He said that the recorded sessions were held at Gregorčič Street 20 (*Gregorčičeva ulica 20*; Government and Presidential Palace) and the recording room was at Gregorčič Street 25.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The buildings were connected with 200 metres (660 feet) of cable.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The system could be abused at several points.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The works at Gregorčič Street 25 were carried out by the construction company SCT, and the computer infrastructure was set up by the companies ADM and TSE.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Košir told that all the people with access to the data were thoroughly checked.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 12 December, after the Secretariat filed a criminal complaint, the Police requested an internal report from the Secretary-General Kamnar.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 15 December, TSE denied having spotted any anomalies in the computer system since it had been installed.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They told that all their employees were checked and that they never received any instruction that would allow for an illegal access.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They also pointed out that the Government was responsible for the security of the system after it had been taken over.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The telephone number of ADM was unavailable.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Rumors about a slow investigation due to long preparation of report by the Secretary-General appeared.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Both the minister of interior and the Secretary-General denied this.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 11 January 2012, an inspectional surveillance, ordered by the Information Commissioner Nataša Pirc Musar, was carried out by the Inspectorate for Protection of Personal Data at the Secretary–General.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] As of 27 January 2012, the findings were not available yet.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The results will influence the decision of the Government about the destruction of the original session recordings.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 26 January 2012, the Secretariat-General of the Government issued a report about an internal investigation that failed to find the perpetrator.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] However, it was found out that the clips were carefully chosen and taken out of context, giving them a different meaning than they would have in the whole.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were alienated after they had been processed in the recording room.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] This significantly narrowed the number of supply locations and the circle of possible suspects.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The highest risk was associated with the human factor.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The Secretariat–General identified the crimes of betrayal of secrets, misuse of position, unauthorized image recording, and an information system attack.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Due to lack of jurisdiction of the Government, further investigation would be carried out by the police.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 27 January 2012, Helena Kamnar, the Secretary-General of the Government, unofficially told for media that three people had access to the Spectiva remote viewing software, and could also watch the sessions from their home.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Kamnar also explained that it was possible to find out who had access in which period but had no information due to the police having confiscated one of the computers.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 28 January 2012, she told that according to the information she had received from the person who allocated the right to use the system, the three people were Janez Janša, the former Secretary-General Božo Predalič, and the former Secretary-General Milan M.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They only had the possibility to use it in their respective terms.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Predalič told that he used it perhaps twice, because he was present at Janša's sessions and did not have the option to use it during Pahor's sessions.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Cvikl told that he refused to use it as it seemed redundant to him and due to security reasons even demanded it to be uninstalled.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The confiscated computers were returned to the Secretary-General on 31 January 2012.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The next morning, Kamnar found the doors of the secretary open and reasoned that someone had broken in.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The Government officially denied any evidence that a criminal act had happened.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] There were guesses whether the two events could be related, but Kamnar decided there would be no investigation, as the possibility of it being successful was slim and she was to be replaced by the new government.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Since February 2012, the government is again led by Janša, and the Secretary-General is again Predalič.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 27 March 2012, the information commissioner reported that the measures for the safeguarding of the recordings were inadequate.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Although the places where the recording device was situated and the recordings were kept were guarded, there were no revision marks on them, which would enable the tracing of their production, usage, viewing and processing.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The law on the protection of personal data was not broken.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] In September 2012, the pre-trial procedure had not been completed yet by the police.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 7 December, the Secretary-General of the Government filed a criminal complaint against the unknown perpetrator and notified about the incident the Criminal Police Directorate and the Office for the Protection of Classified Information.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 8 December, the Slovenian government demanded the removal of the clips from YouTube.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 9 December in the evening, when the publication was reported for the first time by media, there were three clips remaining of the allegedly original five although none had been removed by the host.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] YouTube had removed the clips on 15 December 2011, after a copyright-related demand by the Slovenian Computer Emergency Response Team (SI–CERT).
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] However, on the same day they appeared again, albeit shorter.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were removed again in less than 24 hours.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The clips were republished by users who downloaded them after they have been found by media.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The original perpetrator as well as the uploaders were unknown.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The decision about the destruction of the original governmental recordings has not been made yet, pending the results of an inspectional surveillance.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] After the incident, the recordings were not produced until 26 January.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Since then, they have been made only in audio and have been destroyed immediately after extracts had been made.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They are not transmitted via cable to another building anymore.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] In April 2012, the deputy of the Secretary-General stated that the affair cannot repeat itself, because the government had implemented the traceability of users of governmental session video recordings.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] A tone clip of a closed government session was inadvertently leaked to the website of the Government already on 2 July 2009.
[src:larry-page/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] It showed Katarina Kresal, the former Minister of the Interior, and Irma Pavlinič Krebs, the former Minister of Public Administration, in a wrangle about the number of the policemen in Slovenia, and had a large echo in the public.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] The TLD is of interest due to its utility in regards to branding mobile, web, and other applications.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] The development of the .app domain name began in 2012 after ICANN announced its "New gTLD Program".
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] The program's goal is to expand the current variety of namespaces by an almost unlimited quantity of new entries.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] In January 2012 the program received its first applications and in 2013 first serious investment inflow.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] The first part of the program's domain names were released in late 2014.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] On 25 February 2015, Google won the ICANN Auction of Last Resort for the .app gTLD, via their Charleston Road Registry Inc. company, paying US$25 million.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] Google opened public registration of the domain in May 2018.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] The name "app" is a short form of the word *application* often used in the IT sector.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] This domain name is to be used by developer companies, professionals and enthusiast developers and entrepreneurs applications, app-support services or other useful related products and tools.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] Because of its potential for use as a domain name space for mobile, web, and other applications—as well as for related products—the .app domain name creation is of interest to many development companies, professionals or enthusiast developers.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] The .app gTLD would allow users to easily recognize a Web site dedicated to an application or related product or service, which has benefits in terms of brandability.
[src:larry-page/app-top-level-domain] .app domains are, according to Gandi.net and other Resellers, "a security-focused space, meaning that HTTPS is required for all websites." This is accomplished by including the .app top-level domain on the HSTS preload list, making HTTPS required on all connections to .app websites.
[src:larry-page/dev] The .dev top-level domain is incorporated on the HSTS preload list, requiring HTTPS on all .dev domains without individual HSTS enlistment.
[src:larry-page/dev] Prior to Google's addition of the .dev TLD to the HSTS preload list, it was common for web developers to create ad hoc addresses ending in .dev on their local networks for testing purposes.
[src:larry-page/dev] These local addresses would be created using either fake DNS servers or their own computer's hosts file and would not be accessible to the wider internet.
[src:larry-page/dev] However, after .dev was added to the HSTS preload list, most modern web browsers began refusing to load .dev websites unless they were served over secure HTTPS connections, thereby causing most of these local testing environments to stop functioning.
[src:larry-page/google] It is notable as one of the first gTLDs associated with a specific brand.
[src:larry-page/google] The company's first usage of the TLD was with com.google, an April Fools' Day joke website that hosted a horizontally mirrored version of Google Search.
[src:larry-page/google] The domain currently hosts multiple Alphabet Inc. products and services, and plans exist to move other Alphabet properties to .google as well.
[src:larry-page/google] Google has integrated .google into the HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) preload list.
[src:larry-page/google] This means that all .google domains are hardcoded into major browsers to enforce HTTPS connections, ensuring that users can only access these sites securely.
[src:larry-page/google] This initiative is part of Google's broader effort to enhance web security by eliminating unencrypted HTTP traffic.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page was chief executive officer of Google from 1997 until August 2001 when he was succeeded by Eric Schmidt, and then again from April 2011 until July 2015 when he became CEO of its newly formed parent organization Alphabet Inc.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He held that post until December 4, 2019, when he and Brin stepped down from all executive positions and day-to-day roles within the company.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He remains an Alphabet board member, employee, and one of two controlling shareholders.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page is the co-creator and namesake of PageRank, a search ranking algorithm for Google for which he received the Marconi Prize in 2004 along with co-writer Brin.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Lawrence Edward Page was born on March 26, 1973, in Lansing, Michigan.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] His mother is Jewish; his maternal grandfather later emigrated to Israel, though Page's household while growing up was secular.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] His father, Carl Victor Page Sr., earned a PhD in computer science from the University of Michigan.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] BBC reporter Will Smale described him as a "pioneer in computer science and artificial intelligence".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page's paternal grandparents came from a Protestant background.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page's father was a computer science professor at Michigan State University and his mother Gloria was an instructor in computer programming at Lyman Briggs College at the same institution.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Larry's parents divorced when he was eight years old, but he maintained a good relationship both with his mother Gloria and his father's long-term partner and MSU professor Joyce Wildenthal.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] When Larry Page was six years old, in 1979, his father brought home an Exidy Sorcerer computer, which Larry soon mastered and began using for schoolwork.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] During an interview, Page recalled his childhood home "was usually a mess, with computers, science, and technology magazines and *Popular Science* magazines all over the place", an environment in which he immersed himself.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page was an avid reader during his youth, writing in his 2013 Google founders letter: "I remember spending a huge amount of time pouring [sic] over books and magazines".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] According to writer Nicholas Carlson, the combined influence of Page's home atmosphere and his attentive parents "fostered creativity and invention".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page also played instruments and studied music composition while growing up.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] His parents sent him to music summer camp—Interlochen Arts Camp in Interlochen, Michigan, and Page has mentioned that his musical education inspired his impatience and obsession with speed in computing.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] "In some sense, I feel like music training led to the high-speed legacy of Google for me".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In an interview Page said that "In music, you're very cognizant of time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Time is like the primary thing" and that "If you think about it from a music point of view, if you're a percussionist, you hit something, it's got to happen in milliseconds, fractions of a second".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page was first attracted to computers when he was six years old, as he was able to "play with the stuff lying around"—first-generation personal computers—that had been left by his mother and father.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He became the "first kid in his elementary school to turn in an assignment from a word processor".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] His older brother Carl Victor Page Jr. also taught him to take things apart and before long he was taking "everything in his house apart to see how it worked".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He said that "from a very early age, I also realized I wanted to invent things.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] So I became interested in technology and business.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page attended Okemos Montessori School (now called Montessori Radmoor) in Okemos, Michigan, from ages two to seven (1975 to 1979).
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He attended East Lansing High School, graduating in 1991.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In summer school, he attended Interlochen Center for the Arts at Interlochen, Michigan, playing flute but mainly saxophone for two summers.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page received a Bachelor of Science in Engineering with a major in computer engineering with honors from the University of Michigan in 1995 and a Master of Science in computer science from Stanford University in 1998.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page served as the president of the Beta Epsilon chapter of the Eta Kappa Nu honor society, and was a member of the 1993 "Maize & Blue" University of Michigan Solar Car team.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] As an undergraduate at the University of Michigan, he proposed that the school replace its bus system with a personal rapid-transit system, which is essentially a driverless monorail with separate cars for every passenger.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He also developed a business plan for a company that would use software to build a music synthesizer during this time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] After enrolling in a computer science PhD program at Stanford University, Page was in search of a dissertation theme and considered exploring the mathematical properties of the World Wide Web, understanding its link structure as a huge graph.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] His supervisor, Terry Winograd, encouraged him to pursue the idea, and Page recalled in 2008 that it was the best advice he had ever received.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He also considered doing research on telepresence and self-driving cars during this time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page focused on the problem of finding out which web pages linked to a given page, considering the number and nature of such backlinks as valuable information for that page.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The role of citations in academic publishing would also become pertinent for the research.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] To convert the backlink data gathered by BackRub's web crawler into a measure of importance for a given web page, Brin and Page developed the PageRank algorithm and realized that it could be used to build a search engine far superior to existing ones.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The algorithm relied on a new technology that analyzed the relevance of the backlinks that connected one web page to another.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Combining their ideas, the pair began utilizing Page's dormitory room as a machine laboratory, and extracted spare parts from inexpensive computers to create a device that they used to connect the now nascent search engine with Stanford's broadband campus network.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] After filling Page's room with equipment, they then converted Brin's dorm room into an office and programming center, where they tested their new search engine designs on the Web.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The rapid growth of their project caused Stanford's computing infrastructure to experience problems.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page and Brin used the former's basic HTML programming skills to set up a simple search page for users, as they did not have a web page developer to create anything visually elaborate.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] They also began using any computer part they could find to assemble the necessary computing power to handle searches by multiple users.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] As their search engine grew in popularity among Stanford users, it required additional servers to process the queries.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In August 1996, the initial version of Google, still on the Stanford University website, was made available to Internet users.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] BackRub already exhibited the rudimentary functions and characteristics of a search engine: a query input was entered and it provided a list of backlinks ranked by importance.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page recalled: "We realized that we had a querying tool.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] It gave you a good overall ranking of pages and ordering of follow-up pages." Page said that in mid-1998 they finally realized the further potential of their project: "Pretty soon, we had 10,000 searches a day.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In 1998, Brin and Page incorporated Google, Inc. with the initial domain name of "Googol", derived from a number that consists of one followed by one hundred zeros representing the vast amount of data that the search engine was intended to explore.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Using the garage in their friend Susan Wojcicki's Menlo Park home for $1,700 a month, Page and Brin were able to successfully build the Google search engine.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Following inception, Page appointed himself as CEO, while Brin, named Google's co-founder, was Google's president.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] By June 2000, Google had indexed one billion Internet URLs (Uniform Resource Locators), making it the most comprehensive search engine on the Web at the time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] During his first tenure as CEO, Page embarked on an attempt to fire all of Google's project managers in 2001.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page's plan involved all of Google's engineers reporting to a VP of engineering, who would then report directly to him—Page explained that he did not like non-engineers supervising engineers due to their limited technical knowledge.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Even though Page's new model was unsustainable and led to disgruntlement among the affected employees, his issue with engineers being managed by non-engineering staff gained traction.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page also believed that the faster Google's search engine returned answers, the more it would be used.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He fretted over milliseconds and pushed his engineers—from those who developed algorithms to those who built data centers—to think about lag times.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He also pushed for keeping Google's home page famously sparse in its design because it would help the page load faster.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Eric Schmidt, who had been hired as chairman of Google in March 2001, left his full-time position as the CEO of Novell to take the same role at Google in August of the same year, and Page moved aside to assume the president of products role.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Under Schmidt's leadership, Google underwent a period of major growth and expansion, which included its initial public offering (IPO) on August 20, 2004.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He always acted in consultation with Page and Brin when he embarked on initiatives such as the hiring of an executive team and the creation of a sales force management system.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page remained the boss at Google in the eyes of the employees, as he gave final approval on all new hires, and it was Page who provided the signature for the IPO, the latter making him a billionaire at the age of 30.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page led the acquisition of Android for $50 million in 2005 to fulfill his ambition to place handheld computers in the possession of consumers so that they could access Google anywhere.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The purchase was made without Schmidt's knowledge, but the CEO was not perturbed by the relatively small acquisition.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page became passionate about Android and spent large amounts of time with Android CEO and cofounder Andy Rubin.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] By September 2008, T-Mobile launched the G1, the first phone using Android software and, by 2010, 17.2% of the handset market consisted of Android sales, overtaking Apple for the first time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Android became the world's most popular mobile operating system shortly afterward.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Following a January 2011 announcement, Page officially became the chief executive of Google on April 4, 2011, while Schmidt stepped down to become executive chairman.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] By this time, Google had over $180 billion market capitalization and more than 24,000 employees.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Reporter Max Nisen described the decade prior to Page's second appointment as Google's CEO as Page's "lost decade" saying that while he exerted significant influence at Google via product development and other operations, he became increasingly disconnected and less responsive over time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] As Google's new CEO, Page's two key goals were the development of greater autonomy for the executives overseeing the most important divisions, and higher levels of collaboration, communication, and unity among the teams.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Then Page also formed what the media called the "L-Team", a group of senior vice-presidents who reported directly to him and worked near his office for a portion of the working week.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Additionally, he reorganized the company's senior management, placing a CEO-like manager at the top of Google's most important product divisions, including YouTube, AdWords, and Google Search.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Following a more cohesive team environment, Page declared a new "zero tolerance for fighting" policy that contrasted with his approach during the early days of Google, when he would use his harsh and intense arguments with Brin as an exemplar for senior management.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page had changed his thinking during his time away from the CEO role, as he eventually concluded that ambitious goals required a harmonious team dynamic.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] As part of Page's collaborative rejuvenation process, Google's products and applications were consolidated and underwent an aesthetic overhaul.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] At least 70 of Google's products, features and services were eventually shut down by March 2013, while the appearance and nature of the remaining ones were unified.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Jon Wiley, lead designer of Google Search at the time, codenamed Page's redesign overhaul, which officially commenced on April 4, 2011, "Project Kennedy", based on Page's use of the term "moonshots" to describe ambitious projects in a January 2013 *Wired* interview.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] An initiative named "Kanna" previously attempted to create a uniform design aesthetic for Google's range of products, but it was too difficult at that point in the company's history for one team to drive such change.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] When acquiring products and companies for Google, Page asked whether the business acquisition passed the toothbrush test as an initial qualifier, asking the question "Is it something you will use once or twice a day, and does it make your life better?".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] This approach looked for usefulness above profitability, and long-term potential over near-term financial gain, which has been noted as rare in business acquiring processes.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] With Facebook's influence rapidly expanding during the start of Page's second tenure, he finally responded to the intensive competition with Google's own social network, Google+, in mid-2011.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] After several delays, the social network was released through a very limited field test and was led by Vic Gundotra, Google's then senior vice president of social.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In August 2011, Page announced that Google would spend $12.5 billion to acquire Motorola Mobility.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The purchase was primarily motivated by Google's need to secure patents to protect Android from lawsuits by companies including Apple Inc.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page wrote on Google's official blog on August 15, 2011, that "companies including Microsoft and Apple are banding together in anti-competitive patent attacks on Android.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In 2014, Page sold Motorola Mobility for $2.9 billion to Personal Computer maker, Lenovo which represented a loss in value of $9.5 billion over two years.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page also ventured into hardware and Google unveiled the Chromebook in May 2012.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The hardware product was a laptop that ran on a Google operating system, ChromeOS.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In January 2013, Page participated in a rare interview with *Wired*, in which writer Steven Levy discussed Page's "10X" mentality—Google employees are expected to create products and services that are at least 10 times better than those of its competitors—in the introductory blurb.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] At the May 2013 I/O developers conference in San Francisco, Page delivered a keynote address and said "We're at maybe 1% of what is possible.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Despite the faster change, we're still moving slow relative to the opportunities we have.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] I think a lot of that is because of the negativity [...] Every story I read is Google vs someone else.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] We should be focusing on building the things that don't exist" and that he was "sad the Web isn't advancing as fast as it should be", citing a perceived focus on negativity and zero-sum games among some in the technology sector as a cause.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In response to an audience question, Page noted an issue that Google had been experiencing with Microsoft, whereby the latter made its Outlook program interoperable with Google but did not allow for backward compatibility—he referred to Microsoft's practice as "milking off".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] During the question-and-answer section of his keynote, Page expressed interest in Burning Man, which Brin had previously praised—it was a motivating factor for the latter during Schmidt's hiring process, as Brin liked that Schmidt had attended the week-long annual event.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In September 2013, Page launched the independent Calico initiative, a R&D project in the field of biotechnology.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Google announced that Calico seeks to innovate and make improvements in the field of human health, and appointed Art Levinson, chairman of Apple's board and former CEO of Genentech, to be the new division's CEO.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page's official statement read: "Illness and aging affect all our families.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page participated in a March 2014 TedX conference that was held in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The presentation was scripted by Page's chief PR executive Rachel Whetstone, and Google's CMO Lorraine Twohill, and a demonstration of an artificially intelligent computer program was displayed on a large screen.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page responded to a question about corporations, noting that corporations largely get a "bad rap", which he stated was because they were probably doing the same incremental things they were doing "50 or 20 years ago".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He went on to juxtapose that kind of incremental approach to his vision of Google counteracting calcification through driving technology innovation at a high rate.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page announced a major management restructure in October 2014 so that he would no longer need to be responsible for day-to-day product-related decision making.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page maintained that he would continue as the unofficial "chief product officer".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Subsequent to the announcement, the executives in charge of Google's core products reported to then Google Senior Vice President Sundar Pichai, who reported directly to Page.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In a November 2014 interview, Page stated that he prioritized the maintenance of his "deep knowledge" of Google's products and breadth of projects, as it had been a key motivating factor for team members.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] On August 10, 2015, Page announced on Google's official blog that Google had restructured into a number of subsidiaries of a new holding company known as Alphabet Inc with Page becoming CEO of Alphabet Inc and Sundar Pichai assuming the position of CEO of Google Inc.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page wrote that the motivation behind the reorganization is to make Google "cleaner and more accountable." He also wrote that there was a desire to improve "the transparency and oversight of what we're doing" and to allow greater control of unrelated companies previously within the Google ecosystem.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page has not been on any press conferences since 2015 and has not presented at product launches or earnings calls since 2013.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The *Bloomberg Businessweek* termed the reorganization into Alphabet a clever retirement plan allowing Page to retain control over Google, at the same time relinquishing all responsibilities over it.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Executives at Alphabet describe Page as a "futurist", highly detached from day-to-day business dealings, and more focused on moon-shot projects.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] While some managers of Alphabet companies speak of Page as intensely involved, others say that his rare office check-ins are "akin to a royal visit".
[src:larry-page/larry-page] On December 3, 2019, Larry Page announced that he would step down from the position of Alphabet CEO and be replaced by Google CEO Sundar Pichai.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page and Google co-founder and Alphabet president Sergey Brin announced the change in a joint blog post, "With Alphabet now well-established, and Google and the Other Bets operating effectively as independent companies, it's the natural time to simplify our management structure.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] We've never been ones to hold on to management roles when we think there's a better way to run the company.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page is an investor in Tesla Motors co-founded by friend and fellow billionaire Elon Musk.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He has invested in renewable energy technology, and with the help of Google.org, Google's philanthropic arm, promotes the adoption of plug-in hybrid electric cars and other alternative energy investments.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] He also was a strategic backer in the Opener and Kitty Hawk startups, developing aerial vehicles for consumer travel.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] It was merged into the Wisk Aero joint venture with Boeing in September 2022.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page founded Dynatomics, a Palo Alto-based startup established in 2023, that uses artificial intelligence to optimize product manufacturing processes.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page helped to set up Singularity University, a transhumanist think-tank.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In the early 2000s, Page briefly dated Marissa Mayer, American business leader and former CEO of Yahoo!, who was a Google employee at that time.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] A two-story stucco archway spans the driveway and the home features intricate stucco work, as well as stone and tile in California Arts and Crafts movement style built to resemble de Lemos's family's castle in Spain.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The Pedro de Lemos House was constructed between 1931 and 1941 by de Lemos.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] It is also on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In 2007, Page married Lucinda Southworth on Necker Island, the Caribbean island owned by Richard Branson.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Southworth is a research scientist and the sister of American actress and model Carrie Southworth.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page and Southworth have two children, born in 2009 and 2011 respectively.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In 2009, Page began purchasing properties and tearing down homes adjacent to his home in Palo Alto to make room for a large ecohouse.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The existing buildings were "deconstructed" and the materials donated for reuse.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The ecohouse was designed to "minimize the impact on the environment." Page worked with an arborist to replace some trees that were in poor health with others that used less water to maintain.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page also applied for Green Point Certification, with points given for use of recycled and low or no-VOC (volatile organic compound) materials and for a roof garden with solar panels.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The house's exterior features zinc cladding and plenty of windows, including a wall of sliding-glass doors in the rear.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] It includes eco-friendly elements such as permeable paving in the parking court and a pervious path through the trees on the property.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The 6,000 square feet (560 m2) house also observes other green home design features such as organic architecture building materials and low volatile organic compound paint.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In 2011, Page bought the $45-million 193-foot (59 m) superyacht *Senses*.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Later on, Page announced on his Google+ profile in May 2013 that his right vocal cord is paralyzed from a cold that he contracted the previous summer, while his left cord was paralyzed in 1999, and that the doctors were unable to identify the exact cause.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The Google+ post also revealed that Page had made a large donation to a vocal-cord nerve-function research program at the Voice Health Institute in Boston.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] An anonymous source stated that the donation exceeded $20 million.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In October 2013, *Business Insider* reported that Page's paralysis were caused by an autoimmune disease called Hashimoto's thyroiditis, and prevented him from undertaking Google quarterly earnings conference calls for an indefinite period.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In November 2014, Page's family foundation, the Carl Victor Page Memorial Fund, reportedly holding assets in excess of a billion dollars at the end of 2013, gave $15 million to aid the effort against the Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In August 2021 it was revealed that Page holds a New Zealand resident's visa and had traveled to the country on a medivac flight from Fiji for his son's treatment in New Zealand.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] The flight took place on January 12, 2021.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page had been living in Fiji with his family during the duration of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In 2023, the US Virgin Islands tried several times to serve Page a subpoena in the lawsuit over JPMorgan Chase's links to Jeffrey Epstein.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] Page has purchased multiple private islands across the Caribbean and South Pacific, including the Hans Lollik Island in 2014, Eustatia Island, Cayo Norte in 2018, and Tavarua in 2020.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] In December 2025, Page and Brin, worth a combined $520 billion, terminated or moved out of California sixty limited liability companies that hold their assets.
[src:larry-page/larry-page] A fictionalized version of Larry Page portrayed by actor Ben Feldman appeared in the Showtime drama series *Super Pumped*.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Google's marketing website for .zip states that it is intended "for tying things together or moving really fast".
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] As with a number of other gTLDs, Google require registrants to use HTTPS.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] The qualifier `.zip` is also associated with the widely recognized .zip file format, commonly used for file compression and archiving, and its approval as a gTLD received criticism for the security concerns that may arise as a consequence.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Google opened registration for the .zip and .mov top-level domains to the general public on May 3, 2023.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Its release was immediately met with condemnation from cyber security experts as a result of its similarity with the file format of the same name.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Malwarebytes warned against the use of already recognizable filenames and their confusion with top-level domains, as "plenty of users already have a clear idea that .zip means something completely different".
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Experts cautioned against their use, and noted that the use of .zip filetypes in cybercrime had had "an explosion" in recent years.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Cisco warned against the potential for leaks for personal identifying information.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Researchers also registered similar concern about Google's .mov domain.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Following its release to the general public, .zip domain registrations were one of the most popular new domains registered in mid-2023, during the domain's landrush and early access period.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Security researchers noted high levels of phishing domains and high levels of redirection campaigns.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Shortly after its release, some security vendors blocked access to .zip domains, and new domains under these TLDs began to be scrutinized more carefully.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] One month after its public release in June 2023, there were 13,796 .zip domains registered; which rose to over 14,000 as of November 2024.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] Security researchers found that the rate of malicious registrations for the domain was approximately 0.20%, slightly below the global average of 0.22%.
[src:larry-page/zip-top-level-domain] This was still higher than the abuse rate of 0.06% seen in European ccTLDs.
